Ecological Food Consumption in Urban China -- tChapter 14. From Food Poisoning to Poisonous Food: The Spectrum of Food-Safety Problems in Contemporary China -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFoods are changed not only by those who produce and supply them, but also by those who consume them. Analyzing food without considering changes over time and across space is less meaningful than analyzing it in a global context where tastes, lifestyles, and imaginations cross boundaries and blend with each other, challenging the idea of authenticity. A dish that originated in Beijing and is recreated in New York is not necessarily the same, because although authenticity is often claimed, the form, ingredients, or taste may have changed. The contributors of this volume have expanded the discussion of food to include its social and cultural meanings and functions, thereby using it as a way to explain a culture and its changes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAnthropological linguisticsxResearchxMethodology. 0aDietzEast Asia. 0aFood habitsxResearchxMethodology. 0aFood habitszEast Asia. 0aNutritional anthropologyxResearchxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aBak, Sangmee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Melissa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheung, Sidney C. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeBernardi, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Kyung-Koo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4c